{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018cMrujD3t4dYzHVgxegvn3","type":"tool_result","content":"   435→---\n   436→\n   437→# Additional metrics\n   438→\n   439→\n   440→## Quantile coverage\n   441→\n   442→Quantile coverage for a given quantile level is defined as the proportion of observed values that are smaller than the corresponding predictive quantiles. For example, the 0.5 quantile coverage is the proportion of observed values that are smaller than the 0.5-quantiles of the predictive distribution.\n   443→\n   444→<!-- ## Probability integral transform (PIT) -->\n   445→\n   446→\n   447→\n   448→\n   449→<!-- # Calibration -->\n   450→\n   451→<!-- Calibration or reliability of forecasts is the ability of a model to -->\n   452→<!-- correctly identify its own uncertainty in making predictions. In a model -->\n   453→<!-- with perfect calibration, the observed data at each time point look as if -->\n   454→<!-- they came from the predictive probability distribution at that time. -->\n   455→\n   456→<!-- Equivalently, one can inspect the probability integral transform of the -->\n   457→<!-- predictive distribution at time t, -->\n   458→\n   459→<!-- $$u_t = F_t (x_t)$$ -->\n   460→\n   461→<!-- where $x_t$ is the observed data point at time $t \\text{ in } t_1, …, t_n$, -->\n   462→<!-- n being the number of forecasts, and $F_t$ is the (continuous) predictive -->\n   463→<!-- cumulative probability distribution at time t. If the true probability -->\n   464→<!-- distribution of outcomes at time t is $G_t$ then the forecasts $F_t$ are -->\n   465→<!-- said to be ideal if $F_t = G_t$ at all times $t$. In that case, the -->\n   466→<!-- probabilities ut are distributed uniformly. -->\n   467→\n   468→<!-- In the case of discrete outcomes such as incidence counts, -->\n   469→<!-- the PIT is no longer uniform even when forecasts are ideal. -->\n   470→<!-- In that case a randomised PIT can be used instead: -->\n   471→\n   472→<!-- $$u_t = P_t(k_t) + v \\cdot (P_t(k_t) - P_t(k_t - 1) )$$ -->\n   473→\n   474→<!-- where $k_t$ is the observed count, $P_t(x)$ is the predictive -->\n   475→<!-- cumulative probability of observing incidence $k$ at time $t$, -->\n   476→<!-- $P_t (-1) = 0$ by definition and $v$ is standard uniform and independent -->\n   477→<!-- of $k$. If $P_t$ is the true cumulative -->\n   478→<!-- probability distribution, then $u_t$ is standard uniform. -->\n   479→\n   480→<!-- The function checks whether integer or continuous forecasts were provided. -->\n   481→<!-- It then applies the (randomised) probability integral and tests -->\n   482→<!-- the values $u_t$ for uniformity using the -->\n   483→<!-- Anderson-Darling test. -->\n   484→\n   485→<!-- As a rule of thumb, there is no evidence to suggest a forecasting model is -->\n   486→<!-- miscalibrated if the p-value found was greater than a threshold of $p >= 0.1$, -->\n   487→<!-- some evidence that it was miscalibrated if $0.01 < p < 0.1$, and good -->\n   488→<!-- evidence that it was miscalibrated if $p <= 0.01$. -->\n   489→<!-- In this context it should be noted, though, that uniformity of the -->\n   490→<!-- PIT is a necessary but not sufficient condition of calibration. It should -->\n   491→<!-- also be noted that the test only works given sufficient samples, otherwise the  -->\n   492→<!-- Null hypothesis will often be rejected outright.  -->\n   493→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6be9f240-5be6-4acb-be6b-8e1e3992ff88","uuid":"1bbd6296-cd9d-4226-8684-fcd030318433","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/nikos/github-synced/scoringutils-pipeline/vignettes/scoring-rules.Rmd","content":"---\n\n# Additional metrics\n\n\n## Quantile coverage\n\nQuantile coverage for a given quantile level is defined as the proportion of observed values that are smaller than the corresponding predictive quantiles. For example, the 0.5 quantile coverage is the proportion of observed values that are smaller than the 0.5-quantiles of the predictive distribution.\n\n<!-- ## Probability integral transform (PIT) -->\n\n\n\n\n<!-- # Calibration -->\n\n<!-- Calibration or reliability of forecasts is the ability of a model to -->\n<!-- correctly identify its own uncertainty in making predictions. In a model -->\n<!-- with perfect calibration, the observed data at each time point look as if -->\n<!-- they came from the predictive probability distribution at that time. -->\n\n<!-- Equivalently, one can inspect the probability integral transform of the -->\n<!-- predictive distribution at time t, -->\n\n<!-- $$u_t = F_t (x_t)$$ -->\n\n<!-- where $x_t$ is the observed data point at time $t \\text{ in } t_1, …, t_n$, -->\n<!-- n being the number of forecasts, and $F_t$ is the (continuous) predictive -->\n<!-- cumulative probability distribution at time t. If the true probability -->\n<!-- distribution of outcomes at time t is $G_t$ then the forecasts $F_t$ are -->\n<!-- said to be ideal if $F_t = G_t$ at all times $t$. In that case, the -->\n<!-- probabilities ut are distributed uniformly. -->\n\n<!-- In the case of discrete outcomes such as incidence counts, -->\n<!-- the PIT is no longer uniform even when forecasts are ideal. -->\n<!-- In that case a randomised PIT can be used instead: -->\n\n<!-- $$u_t = P_t(k_t) + v \\cdot (P_t(k_t) - P_t(k_t - 1) )$$ -->\n\n<!-- where $k_t$ is the observed count, $P_t(x)$ is the predictive -->\n<!-- cumulative probability of observing incidence $k$ at time $t$, -->\n<!-- $P_t (-1) = 0$ by definition and $v$ is standard uniform and independent -->\n<!-- of $k$. If $P_t$ is the true cumulative -->\n<!-- probability distribution, then $u_t$ is standard uniform. -->\n\n<!-- The function checks whether integer or continuous forecasts were provided. -->\n<!-- It then applies the (randomised) probability integral and tests -->\n<!-- the values $u_t$ for uniformity using the -->\n<!-- Anderson-Darling test. -->\n\n<!-- As a rule of thumb, there is no evidence to suggest a forecasting model is -->\n<!-- miscalibrated if the p-value found was greater than a threshold of $p >= 0.1$, -->\n<!-- some evidence that it was miscalibrated if $0.01 < p < 0.1$, and good -->\n<!-- evidence that it was miscalibrated if $p <= 0.01$. -->\n<!-- In this context it should be noted, though, that uniformity of the -->\n<!-- PIT is a necessary but not sufficient condition of calibration. It should -->\n<!-- also be noted that the test only works given sufficient samples, otherwise the  -->\n<!-- Null hypothesis will often be rejected outright.  -->\n","numLines":59,"startLine":435,"totalLines":493}}}
